INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (2,48,'2017-06-21 18:23:40','2017-06-21 18:23:40','<h1>This is MMS Monitoring Service web page!</h1>\r\n<h1></h1>&nbsp;\r\n<h2>What is Maritime Connectivity Platform (formerly, Maritime Cloud)?</h2>\r\nThe objective of the Maritime Connectivity Platform is to provide a secure platform to enable maritime stakeholders to securely access technical services to gain further information for decision-making onboard and ashore during a voyage from berth-to-berth. The Maritime Connectivity Platform shall not be considered as a product but as a common communication framework for maritime users to register, discover, and use technical services such as route optimization or weather forecast. Clients and Services communicate by standardized web service technologies supported by standard services to set up and facilitate the communication.\r\n\r\nSee more, <a href=\"https://maritimeconnectivity.net/\">https://maritimeconnectivity.net/</a>\r\n<h2>What is MMS?</h2>\r\nMMS is abbreviation of Maritime Messaging Service.\r\n\r\nThe MMS is a proposed messaging service intended to offer transparent seamless information transfer across different communication links in a carrier agnostic and geolocation context sensitive manner.\r\n\r\nThe MMS primarily addresses ship-shore connectivity and will be based on internet connectivity, yet any number of alternative communication services may be connected to and utilized by the MMS via dedicated gateways. This way, a message, sent by one specific ship using INMARSAT access to the MMS, may be received via a VSAT terminal on another ship, an HF data connection on yet another ship, or a VTS operator on a DSL landline internet connection.\r\n\r\nEach communication service will impose technology and situation specific limitations in terms of restrictions to capabilities, bandwidth availability, size of transferrable data packages, latencies, etc. – but basic transfer of text or structured data (e.g. using XML) will be possible.\r\n\r\nThus, if a maritime actor wishes to transfer information to another maritime actor or is in need of multicast information to a group of actors, the MMS can ensure delivery across whichever communication links is currently active at each relevant actor. Actors in a multicast group thus do not need to be within range of a single communication link, and actors inside a geographic multicast may be addressable by an information provider, although the identity and exact position of the actors are unknown to the provider of information. In case a ship temporarily has no active communication link, the MMS will function as a prioritized store-and-forward queue of messages where the validity period can be defined for the messages sent.\r\n\r\nThrough mechanisms of protocol level acknowledgements, the delivery of information via the MMS can be quality assuring.\r\n\r\nSince heterogeneous communication links are available at sea, a ship may change its communication link at any time by other communication link with better quality. If the communication link is changed, the network locator of the ship can be changed. If the locator of the destination ship changes unexpectedly, the\r\nmessage to the ship\'s previous locator cannot reach the ship. Thus, it is difficult to transmit a message using only the locater based address in a situation where the ship\'s locator can be changed.\r\n\r\nTo implement MMS, we are considering to apply a method in order to correctly transmit the message, even when the ship\'s locator changes dynamically. Within SMART-Navigation, each ship has a unique identifier and the MMS maps the ship\'s identifier to the currently accessible locator. The locator of ships can be changed at any time and the MMS has the locator which are currently available to communicate with. When a message sender sends a message to MMS with destination identifier of a destination ship, the MMS forwards the message to the current up-to-date locator of the ship.\r\n\r\nThe MMS is a communication brokerage service that provides additional communication patterns (multicasting and geocasting) and uses existing seamless roaming systems or even non-IP based communication systems.','MMS Monitoring Service','','publish','closed','open','','sample-page','','','2018-06-28 22:06:28','2018-06-28 13:06:28','',0,'http://192.168.0.5/?page_id=2',0,'page','',0),(5,48,'2017-06-22 03:49:58','2017-06-21 18:49:58','<h1>This is MC MMS Monitoring Service web page!</h1>\r\n<h2>What is MC?</h2>\r\nMC is abbreviation of Maritime Cloud.\r\n\r\nThe objective of the Maritime Cloud is to provide a secure platform to enable maritime stakeholders to securely access technical services to gain further information for decision-making onboard and ashore during a voyage from berth-to-berth. The Maritime Cloud shall not be considered as a product but as a common communication framework for maritime users to register, discover, and use technical services such as route optimization or weather forecast. Clients and Services communicate by standardized web service technologies supported by standard services to set up and facilitate the communication.\r\n\r\nSee more,<a href=\"http://maritimecloud.net/\"> http://maritimecloud.net/</a>\r\n<h2>What is MMS?</h2>\r\nMMS is abbreviation of Maritime Messaging Service.\r\n\r\nThe MMS is a proposed messaging service intended to offer transparent seamless information transfer across different communication links in a carrier agnostic and geolocation context sensitive manner.\r\n\r\nThe MMS primarily addresses ship-shore connectivity and will be based on internet connectivity, yet any number of alternative communication services may be connected to and utilized by the MMS via dedicated gateways. This way, a message, sent by one specific ship using INMARSAT access to the MMS, may be received via a VSAT terminal on another ship, an HF data connection on yet another ship, or a VTS operator on a DSL landline internet connection.\r\n\r\nEach communication service will impose technology and situation specific limitations in terms of restrictions to capabilities, bandwidth availability, size of transferrable data packages, latencies, etc. – but basic transfer of text or structured data (e.g. using XML) will be possible.\r\n\r\nThus, if a maritime actor wishes to transfer information to another maritime actor or is in need of multicast information to a group of actors, the MMS can ensure delivery across whichever communication links is currently active at each relevant actor. Actors in a multicast group thus do not need to be within range of a single communication link, and actors inside a geographic multicast may be addressable by an information provider, although the identity and exact position of the actors are unknown to the provider of information. In case a ship temporarily has no active communication link, the MMS will function as a prioritized store-and-forward queue of messages where the validity period can be defined for the messages sent.\r\n\r\nThrough mechanisms of protocol level acknowledgements, the delivery of information via the MMS can be quality assuring.\r\n\r\nSince heterogeneous communication links are available at sea, a ship may change its communication link at any time by other communication link with better quality. If the communication link is changed, the network locator of the ship can be changed. If the locator of the destination ship changes unexpectedly, the\r\nmessage to the ship\'s previous locator cannot reach the ship. Thus, it is difficult to transmit a message using only the locater based address in a situation where the ship\'s locator can be changed.\r\n\r\nTo implement MMS, we are considering to apply a method in order to correctly transmit the message, even when the ship\'s locator changes dynamically. Within SMART-Navigation, each ship has a unique identifier and the MMS maps the ship\'s identifier to the currently accessible locator. The locator of ships can be changed at any time and the MMS has the locator which are currently available to communicate with. When a message sender sends a message to MMS with destination identifier of a destination ship, the MMS forwards the message to the current up-to-date locator of the ship.\r\n\r\nThe MMS is a communication brokerage service that provides additional communication patterns (multicasting and geocasting) and uses existing seamless roaming systems or even non-IP based communication systems.','MMS Monitoring Service','','inherit','closed','closed','','2-revision-v1','','','2017-06-22 03:49:58','2017-06-21 18:49:58','',2,'http://192.168.0.5/index.php/2017/06/22/2-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(35,48,'2017-06-22 04:53:06','2017-06-21 19:53:06','','cropped-hamburg-2111613_960_720.jpg','','inherit','open','closed','','cropped-hamburg-2111613_960_720-jpg','','','2017-06-22 04:53:06','2017-06-21 19:53:06','',0,'http://192.168.0.5/wp-content/uploads/2017/06/cropped-hamburg-2111613_960_720.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(51,48,'2017-06-22 12:24:07','2017-06-22 03:24:07','<b>Log level: info</b>\n\n[insert_php]\n\n$directory = \"/var/mms/logs/\";\n\n$myfile = fopen($directory.\"mms-server.html\", \"r\") or die(\"Unable to open file!\");\nif ($myfile ) {\nwhile (($line = fgets($myfile )) !== false) {\n// process the line read.\n\nif ((strpos($line, \'INFO\') !== false) || (strpos($line, \'WARN\') !== false) || (strpos($line, \'ERROR\') !== false)) { echo $line; }\n}\n\nfclose($myfile );\n} else {\n// error opening the file.\n}\n\n[/insert_php]','Logging page','','trash','closed','closed','','logging-page__trashed','','','2019-06-11 18:31:26','2019-06-11 09:31:26','',0,'http://192.168.0.5/?page_id=51',0,'page','',0),(52,48,'2017-06-22 12:24:07','2017-06-22 03:24:07','empty','empty page','','inherit','closed','closed','','51-revision-v1','','','2017-06-22 12:24:07','2017-06-22 03:24:07','',51,'http://192.168.0.5/index.php/2017/06/22/51-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(60,48,'2017-06-22 12:39:04','2017-06-22 03:39:04','[insert_php]\r\n\r\n$myfile = fopen(\"/var/www/html/mms-server.log\", \"r\") or die(\"Unable to open file!\");\r\necho fread($myfile,filesize(\"/var/www/html/mms-server.log\"));\r\nfclose($myfile);\r\n\r\n[/insert_php]','Logging page','','inherit','closed','closed','','51-revision-v1','','','2017-06-22 12:39:04','2017-06-22 03:39:04','',51,'http://192.168.0.5/index.php/2017/06/22/51-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(62,48,'2017-06-22 12:49:13','2017-06-22 03:49:13','<button id=\"show-managing-panel\" style=\"background-color: #6699ff;\" type=\"button\">Show Managing Panel</button>\n<div id=\"managing-panel\" style=\"display: none;\">\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<!--\n<tr>\n<td><a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Set a Service Polling Method as Normal. Service MRN=</a><input id=\"svc-mrn-normal\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"normal-polling-button\" type=\"button\">Set</button>\nNormal polling is that a MMS client periodically sends polling request to the MMS server.\n<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Set a Service Polling Method as Long. Service MRN=</a><input id=\"svc-mrn-long\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"long-polling-button\" type=\"button\">Set</button>\nLong polling is that a MMS client sends a polling request to the MMS server and waits until a message arrives.\n<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Remove a Service Polling Method. Service MRN=</a><input id=\"svc-mrn-remove\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"remove-polling-button\" type=\"button\">Remove</button>\nRemove the polling method and set it as the default polling method.\nDefault polling method of a service is normal polling.</td>\n</tr>\n-->\n<tr>\n<td><a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Add MNS entry having MRN=</a><input id=\"add-mrn\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">IP=</a><input id=\"ip\" style=\"width: 160px;\" pattern=\"^([0-9]{1,3}\\.){3}[0-9]{1,3}$\" required=\"\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">PortNumber=</a><input id=\"port\" style=\"width: 80px;\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Model=</a><input id=\"model\" style=\"width: 40px;\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"add-mns-entry-submit\" type=\"button\">Add</button>\n<strong>Maritime Name System (MNS) Dummy</strong> saves MRN-locator mapping information entries. It appears under the managing panel.\nModel <strong>1</strong> is polling client model. Model <strong>2</strong> is service provider (server) model.\nModel <strong>1</strong> need not have correct IP and port number. (e.g. IP=1.1.1.1 and port number=0)\nModel <strong>2</strong> must have correct IP and port number that MMS server can access.\nBe careful that model <strong>2</strong> may not receive messages due to its firewalls, NAT or line sharer(공유기), etc.\n<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Remove MNS entry having MRN=</a><input id=\"remove-mrn\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"remove-mns-entry-submit\" type=\"button\">Remove</button></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Add the MRN you are debugging. MRN=</a><input id=\"add-mrn-being-debugged\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"add-mrn-being-debugged-submit\" type=\"button\">Add</button>\nRegister the MRN in <strong>MRNs being debugged</strong>.\nBegin collecting logs related to the MRN being debugged.\n<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Remove the MRN you are not debugging anymore. MRN=</a><input id=\"remove-mrn-being-debugged\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"remove-mrn-being-debugged-submit\" type=\"button\">Remove</button>\nRemove the MRN from <strong>MRNs being debugged</strong>.\nStop collecting logs related to the MRN being debugged. Then remove the logs.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td><a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Add the ID consuming realtime log service. ID=</a><input id=\"add-id-realtime-log-ids\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"add-id-realtime-log-ids-submit\" type=\"button\">Add</button>\nRegister the ID in <strong>Realtime log service consumer IDs</strong>.\nBegin collecting realtime logs for the ID.\n<a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">Remove the ID not consuming realtime log service anymore. ID=</a><input id=\"remove-id-realtime-log-ids\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"remove-id-realtime-log-ids-submit\" type=\"button\">Remove</button>\nRemove the ID from <strong>Realtime log service consumer IDs</strong>.\nStop collecting logs for the ID. Then remove the logs.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<button id=\"hide-managing-panel\" style=\"background-color: #6699ff;\" type=\"button\">Hide Managing Panel</button>\n\n</div>\n&nbsp;\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td><a style=\"font-size: 12pt;\">The MRN you are debugging now. MRN=</a><input id=\"mrn-being-debugged\" type=\"text\">&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"mrn-being-debugged-submit\" type=\"button\">view logs</button>&nbsp;&nbsp;<button id=\"return-to-status-page\" type=\"button\">return</button>\nOnly the logs related to the MRN being debugged are shown.\nFirst, the MRN must be registered in <strong>MRNs being debugged</strong>.\nIn order to regiser a MRN in <strong>MRNs being debugged</strong>, use the function in <strong>the managing panel</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"padding-left: 14.4px;\">MMS\'s Maritime Resource Name: <strong>urn:mrn:smart-navi:device:mms1</strong>. Addresses: <strong>http://192.168.0.104:8088</strong>, <strong>https://192.168.0.104:444</strong>.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>[includeme src=\"\" frameborder=\"0\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1200\" id=\"mms-status\"]</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<div id=\"invisible-container\" style=\"display: none;\"></div>','MMS status page','','publish','closed','closed','','mms-status-page','','','2019-06-10 22:17:14','2019-06-10 13:17:14','',0,'http://192.168.0.5/?page_id=62',0,'page','',0),(63,48,'2017-06-22 12:49:13','2017-06-22 03:49:13','','MMS status page','','inherit','closed','closed','','62-revision-v1','','','2017-06-22 12:49:13','2017-06-22 